        <span class="nav-tag">open standard · open-core</span>
      </nav>
    </div>
  </header>

  <main class="article">
    <header class="article-head">
      <p class="crumbs"><a href="/">determs</a> / privacy</p>
      <h1>Privacy</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Determs is an open-source project, and determs.com is a static site built to collect as little as possible.</p>
      <p class="meta">Last updated June 2026</p>
    </header>

    <article class="article-body">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>No tracking.</strong> No analytics, no cookies, no fingerprinting, no third-party scripts. Fonts are self-hosted — nothing loads from an external CDN. The site stores nothing in your browser and sends your activity nowhere.</li>
        <li><strong>No accounts, no forms.</strong> The site asks you for no personal data. There is nothing to sign up for and nothing to submit.</li>
        <li><strong>Server logs.</strong> Like any web server, the host (Caddy, on an Infomaniak VPS) keeps standard access logs — including IP addresses — briefly, for security and operation. They are not used to profile or track you.</li>
        <li><strong>Private by design.</strong> This mirrors how Determs itself works: records and proofs use only digests (hashes); the underlying decision data never leaves your environment.</li>
        <li><strong>Contact &amp; data requests.</strong> Anything — including a request about data the project holds — start a thread on <a href="https://github.com/determs-com/determs/discussions" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub Discussions</a>.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>No personal data is sold or shared. Governed by Swiss data-protection law (revised FADP).</p>
    </article>

    <footer class="article-foot">
      <span>determs · open standard for verifiable automated decisions</span>
      <a href="/" class="plain">← Back to determs.com</a>
    </footer>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
